<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-0dTY-Nfz7CstqHdOU3hKPw" name="uam_logical_locations_model,_2x718M6kEdymj4NXv8-FYA" guid="-0dTY-Nfz7CstqHdOU3hKPw" authors="DW Enstrom" changeDate="2015-02-23T12:22:04.355-0500" changeDescription="new" version="2.0.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Logical Locations viewpoint describes the structure of locations (each of which contain activities, roles, and&#xD;
    processes) that when structured into a model define the complete set of locations, and their interrelationships, at&#xD;
    which the system under study operates. At the logical level locations are abstracted, likely into types of locations.&#xD;
    For example a bank operates at many locations, but each one can be abstracted into Logical Locations such as Head&#xD;
    Office, Main Branch, Branch, Full Service ATM, and ATM among others.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Logical_Perspective__Logical_Locations_Model&quot; name=&quot;XE_Logical_Perspective__Logical_Locations_Model&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The objective is to clearly define the locations involved, and the sorts of services provided within and between them.&#xD;
    This information is important in deciding on the architecture for applications and services, so that they operate&#xD;
    effectively, over a slow speed WAN for example. Security implications are also eventually derived from this model for&#xD;
    example; at this level some of these defined &quot;locations&quot; may include security domains and zones.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It is important to clearly define the locations and the relationships between them in terms of the services&#xD;
    (activities/workflows) provided and facilities provided (data/voice, etc.).&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <purpose>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Logical Locations Model defines the structure of logical locations, each of which contain systems, roles&amp;nbsp;and&#xD;
    processes.&amp;nbsp;The model defines the set of logical locations, and their interrelationships, where the system&#xD;
    operates. The activities at each location are defined, along with the logical deployment of other aspects.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
  <representationOptions>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>UML Representation&lt;/strong>: Package stereotyped as «LPL_LLM» containing deployment diagrams.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A &lt;strong>Logical Locations Model&lt;/strong> may have the following properties:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Introduction:&lt;/b> A textual description that serves as a brief introduction to the model.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Packages:&lt;/b> The packages in the model, representing a hierarchy&amp;nbsp;(contained within the Logical Perspective&#xD;
        package).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Nodes:&lt;/b> The nodes in the model, owned by the packages stereotyped as «LPL_Location», «LPL_Domain»,&#xD;
        «LPL_Zone», «LPL_Server», etc.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Relationships:&lt;/b> The relationships in the model, owned by the packages stereotyped as «LPL_Comms».&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;b>Diagrams:&lt;/b> The diagrams in the model, owned by the packages.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>A Logical Locations Model is created to illustrate the conceptual location at which the &quot;system&quot; has a presence. Most&#xD;
things defined at this stage will go on to be described in detail in the Logical&amp;nbsp;Perspective and Technical&#xD;
Perspective. This artifact is enclosed within the Logical Perspective artifact. &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Logical Locations Model is a way of expressing the business conducted at and between locations where it operates.&#xD;
    Locations are logical, and include &quot;locations&quot; based upon security concepts, see: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/whitepapers/uam_security_reference_model_3EA07B63.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_KGs_oMX8EdyDYN2-y9-AqA&quot;>Whitepaper: A Reference Model for Enterprise Security&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;(i.e., Domains and&#xD;
    Zones). The types of locations and interactions between them are what are modeled. The business activities supported or&#xD;
    provided at each location are also described.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Decide on the following:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The sub-package structure for the Logical Location Model package: function-based structure or coherence/coupling&#xD;
        based;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Properties to include;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Whether or not any extensions to the Unified Modeling Language (UML) are needed; additional stereotypes or&#xD;
        profile&amp;nbsp;for example;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The level of formality&amp;nbsp;and detail in the model (see&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_logical_pers_1ABDA187.html&quot; guid=&quot;_aiIn4Ou6Edytvcf-4U2D3Q&quot;>Guideline:&#xD;
        Logical Perspective&lt;/a>);&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Whether a single model or multiple models will be used.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p class=&quot;BodyTable&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 6pt 0in&quot;>&#xD;
    The modeling elements are too extensive to include, see:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/supportingmaterials/uam_lpl_simple_AB1449E6.html&quot; guid=&quot;_uOZlsEWJEeOfR_FtRm9PUg&quot;>Supporting&#xD;
    Material: LPL Summary&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></representationOptions>
